data}\label{model-output-compared-to-data}}

the range of estimated LAI for each tree species, parameters were
compiled into ensembles to be representative of each of the tree
species. Out of more than 5,000 parameter sets, we ended up with 366 for
coast live oak, 533 for victorian box, 404 for canary island pine, 86
eucalyptus, and 217 california sycamore.

Model outputs of LAI for the year 2011 fell within the range of
estimated LAI for each species, although the median of the parameter
ensembles is slightly lower than the median of the remotely sensed data.
In statistical correlation tests, all tree species show positive
association between the modelled and observed LAI values, with
significant p-values.

 We used percent changes in NDVI to compare with changes in LAI in the
model. We had data from 2011, a pre-drought wet year, 2014, the warmest
year of the drought, and 2017, a wet year following the drought period.
The variation in the NDVI data is due to different trees (of the same
species) within the dataset. The variation in the model LAI is due to
parameter uncertainty.

Parameter ensembles were filtered to be within the range of percent
differences between 2011-2014 and 2011-2017. To test for similarities
between the two sets of percent differences, the modelled outputs were
randomly sampled from each tree species parameter ensemble to 50 sets,
and tested against 50 percent differences in NDVI usnig a Mann-Whitney
test. The results were variable across tree species, with QUAG, PICA,
and PLRA showing significant differences in the decline in LAI / NDVI
from 2011-2014. Only EUGL and PLRA show significant differences for the
2011-2017 percent differences. Despite these differences in medians, the
results for each tree species parameter ensemble fall within the range
of the data, and are not out of the range of possiblity.

\hypertarget{drought-resistance-and-resilience}{%
\subsection{2. Drought resistance and
resilience}\label{drought-resistance-and-resilience}}

We calculated the resistance to drought as the ratio to pre-drought
conditions in 2011 during the drought from 2012-2016. We calculated
resilience as the ratio of post-drought, after a wet season in 2017, to
pre-drought conditions in 2011. We did this for the annual average LAI
and net primary production (NPP)

\includegraphics{Results_ch1_files/figure-latex/resilience-1.pdf}

For LAI resistance and resilience:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  In the historic drought scenario, most of the trees had a resistance
  0.75 or greater, and a resilience of 0.9 or greater
\item
  Cooler temperatures increased resistance at the beginning of the
  drought for all trees, but then showed lower resilience after the wet
  year
\item
  Extreme hot temperatures had the least resistance and lower resilience
  relative to the other temperature scenarios
\item
  The victorian box and coast live oak, representative of two broadleaf
  evergreen trees, both have larger ranges for resistance and resilience
  to drought, with some of the lowest values in the set, dropping below
  0.50.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}

  to 0.75, meaning after one wet season only 75\% of pre-drought NPP was
  reached.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{interannual-changes-to-carbon-fluxes-during-drought}{%
\subsection{3. Interannual changes to carbon fluxes during
drought}\label{interannual-changes-to-carbon-fluxes-during-drought}}

When looking at changes in water fluxes, there are minimal differences
across temperature scenarios and trees during drought years. This is
likely due to transpiration demands exceeding water availability, and
all of the water is transpired no matter the temperature or tree
parameters.

For the below plot, we took the median daily carbon fluxes across all
parameter ensembles for each temperature scenario. We separated into
drought and wet years, where drought years include 2012-2016 and wet
years include 2011 and 2017.

\includegraphics{Results_ch1_files/figure-latex/carbon-1.pdf}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  During drought years, GPSN is relatively less in winter compared to
  wet years, with summer values approaching zero.
\item
  Winter GPSN increases with temperature, but higher temperatures also
  decrease summer GPSN
\item
  Net respiration amounts generally increase with temperature, but there
  are relatively small differences across seasons and dry v. wet years
\item
  The median NPP of all scenaerios varies with temperature, although all
  temperature scenarios include a period of time when the trees become a
  carbon source during the drought. During wet years only the extreme
  heat scenario had negative NPP
\item
  Winter values of NPP are comparable across dry and wet years - the
  changes in net annual NPP is mainly due to the decrease in summer
  during drought
\item
  There is a sharper decline from higher winter NPP to summer lows
  during drought, which is explored more below 
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{seasonal-differences-in-gpsn-scross-scenarios}{%
\subsubsection{Seasonal differences in GPSN scross
scenarios}\label{seasonal-differences-in-gpsn-scross-scenarios}}

To further explore the changes to seasonal carbon fluxes during drought,
we calculated changes in peak gross photosynthesis for each species
parameter ensemble and temperature scenario. We looked at the day of the
year when 50\% of GPSN is reached.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  During drought years, half of the GPSN is reached earlier in the year
  compared to wet years
\item
  The changes between tree species may have to do with the leaf-on and
  leaf-off periods set in the model
\item
  cooler temperatures have longer periods of GPSN through the year, but
  lower net amounts, while warmer temperatures have higher net amounts,
  but they are reached earlier in the year ** with this plot, the y-axis
  doesn't make sense, need to edit **
\end{itemize}

\includegraphics{Results_ch1_files/figure-latex/days-1.pdf}

\hypertarget{sensitivity-analysis-results}{%
\subsection{4. Sensitivity Analysis
results}\label{sensitivity-analysis-results}}

There were two metrics used to look at Sobol indices in the sensitivity
analysis. The first was the average LAI in 2011, as the pre-drought
conditions. The second was the resilience of LAI, or the ratio of the
average LAI in 2017 to the average LAI in 2011.

The parameter ranges for the sensitivity analysis differed between
evergreen and deciduous tree types, as the limits set on some of the
parameters varied enough in the literature to do two separate analysis.

For both metrics and tree types, we looked at the parameters with the
highest total rank indices. The top 5 for each group are shown in the
tables below.

\includegraphics{predroughtLAI_SA_table.png}

For the 2011 LAI, evergreen parameters that had the largest sensitivity
included leaf and branch turnover rates (epc.leaf\_turnover,
epc.branch\_turnover), specific leaf area (epc.proj\_sla), and two
waring parameters (epc.waring\_pa, epc.waring\_pb), which are parameters
within RHESSys that affect carbon allocation to leaves and roots, based
on the allocation strategy from Landsberg and Waring, 1997.

For the deciduous type, LAI is also sensitive to the waring parameters
and leaf turnover rates, as well as the allocation ratio between stem
carbon and leaf carbon (epc.alloc\_stemc\_leafc). Pore size index was
also sensitive for both tree types, which affects how much water is
available in the soil.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics{LAIresil_SA_table.png}
\caption{Table of LAI resilience Sobol index results}
\end{figure}

For LAI drought resilience, there were similar parameters that stood out
including leaf and branch turnover rates, and one of the waring
parameters. In evergreen trees, the parameter epc.root\_distrib\_parm
was significant; this affects how deep the roots are able to grow. For
the deciduous type, fine root turnover was important, as well as carbon
parameters including the fraction of carbon to be used each year
(epc.storage\_transfer\_prop), the amount of fPAR used for
photosynthesis (epc.netpabs\_sunlit).

Both soil parameters were important for resilience, although the level
of importance varied. For broadleaf, resilience was more sensitive to
soil air entry pressure (psi\_air\_entry), and for deciduous it was more
sensitive to the pore size index, similar to the actual pre-drought LAI.
